[[Major-General]] '''Sir John Braithwaite, 1st Baronet''' (3 February 1739 - 16 August 1803) was Commander-in-Chief of the [[Madras Army]].

==Military career==
Educated at [[Westminster School]], Braithwaite was commissioned as an [[ensign (rank)|ensign]] in the [[53rd (Shropshire) Regiment of Foot|53rd Regiment of Foot]] on 6 November 1765.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnw.co.uk/auction-archive/catalogue-archive/lot.php?auction_id=63&lot_id=42050|title=Brian Ritchie Collection (Part 1)|publisher=Dix Noonan Webb|accessdate=7 June 2014}}</ref> Promoted to [[lieutenant-colonel]] on 22 October 1772, he seized the [[Maharaja of Vizianagram]]'s fort during a local dispute on 28 August 1777.<ref name=bio/> He was then given command of a brigade which included one battalion of Europeans, the [[63rd Palamcottah Light Infantry|3rd Carnatic Battalion]], the [[63rd Palamcottah Light Infantry|4th Carnatic Battalion]] and the [[79th Carnatic Infantry|20th Carnatic Battalion]]: with this army he defeated a French force at [[Mahé, India|Mahé]] in March 1779.<ref name=bio/>

In Summer 1780 [[Hyder Ali]] invaded the [[Karnataka|Carnatic]] with over 60,000 men precipitating the [[Second Anglo-Mysore War]]: he took Braithwaite prisoner at [[Srirangapatna|Seringapatam]] in February 1782 and held him captive for two years.<ref name=bio/> Braithwaite became acting Commander-in-Chief of the [[Madras Army]] in August 1792, conducting the successful [[Siege of Pondicherry (1793)|Siege of Pondicherry]] in 1793 and remained in that role until 1796.<ref name=bio/>

Braithwaite was adjutant-general of the force that defeated [[Tipu Sultan]] at the [[Siege of Seringapatam (1799)|Siege of Seringapatam]] in April 1799 so concluding the [[Fourth Anglo-Mysore War]].<ref name=bio/> He became Commander-in-Chief of the [[Madras Army]] in January 1800<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h2nkEiSSDaYC&pg=PA548&lpg=PA548&dq=Lieutenant+General+Ross+Lang&source=bl&ots=lut7_7C7U2&sig=Zw2HHyGqsbcFDQ-KUFCSXV-tDu8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Z92SU9ykCseM7Ab3qYGQCQ&ved=0CCwQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Lieutenant%20General%20Ross%20Lang&f=false|title=Indian Records Series Vestiges of Old Madras|first=Henry Davidson |last=Love|year=2006|publisher=Asian Educational Services, India|page=548|isbn=978-8120603202}}</ref> and, after retiring in 1801, he was created a Baronet on 18 December 1802 and died at his home in [[London]] in August 1803.<ref name=bio/>

